<h2>What Is Base64 Encoding and When Do You Need It</h2>

<p>Base64 is a binary-to-text encoding scheme that represents binary data using a set of 64 ASCII characters (A–Z, a–z, 0–9, <code>+</code>, <code>/</code>). It converts every 3 bytes of binary data into 4 ASCII characters, increasing the size by approximately 33% but making the data safe to transmit through systems that only handle text.</p>

<h3>Common Developer Use Cases</h3>

<ul>
  <li><strong>HTTP Basic Authentication:</strong> The Authorization header encodes <code>username:password</code> as Base64 — <code>Authorization: Basic dXNlcjpwYXNz</code></li>
  <li><strong>JSON Web Tokens (JWT):</strong> The header and payload sections of a JWT are Base64URL-encoded JSON objects. Decoding them reveals the token claims.</li>
  <li><strong>Data URIs:</strong> Embedding images directly in HTML or CSS as <code>data:image/png;base64,iVBOR...</code> avoids an extra HTTP request</li>
  <li><strong>API payloads:</strong> Binary data like images or files transmitted in JSON APIs must be Base64-encoded since JSON only supports text</li>
  <li><strong>Email attachments:</strong> MIME encoding uses Base64 for binary attachments in email messages</li>
  <li><strong>Environment variables:</strong> Storing binary secrets (certificates, keys) in environment variables often requires Base64 encoding</li>
</ul>

<p>For a deeper dive into how Base64 works under the hood, including its variants and security considerations, see our <a href="/blog/base64-encoding-explained">Base64 encoding explained guide</a>.</p>

<h2>Base64 vs Base64URL: An Important Distinction</h2>

<p>Standard Base64 uses <code>+</code> and <code>/</code> as the 62nd and 63rd characters, and <code>=</code> for padding. These characters have special meaning in URLs, which causes problems when Base64-encoded data appears in query strings or path segments.</p>

<p>Base64URL solves this by substituting <code>-</code> for <code>+</code> and <code>_</code> for <code>/</code>, and omitting or making padding optional. JWTs always use Base64URL encoding. Any tool you use should clearly distinguish between the two variants and support both.</p>

