<h3>Character Set and Encoding Options</h3>
<p>String-to-Base64 encoding depends on the character set of the source string. UTF-8 is the standard for web applications, but some legacy systems use Latin-1 or other encodings. A tool that lets you specify the character set prevents subtle bugs when working with non-ASCII text.</p>

<h3>Client-Side Processing</h3>
<p>Base64 is frequently used with secrets — API keys, passwords, certificates, tokens. Any tool that uploads your data to a server to process it is a security liability. Client-side tools that run entirely in the browser are the only safe choice for encoding sensitive data.</p>

