<h2>Practical Base64 Examples Every Developer Should Know</h2>

<h3>Decoding a JWT Payload</h3>
<p>A JWT looks like three Base64URL-encoded segments separated by dots: <code>header.payload.signature</code>. To read the payload, take the middle segment and Base64URL-decode it:</p>

<pre><code># JWT payload segment (Base64URL encoded)
eyJ1c2VySWQiOiIxMjMiLCJlbWFpbCI6InVzZXJAZXhhbXBsZS5jb20iLCJleHAiOjE3NDAwMDAwMDB9

# Decoded JSON
{
  "userId": "123",
  "email": "user@example.com",
  "exp": 1740000000
}</code></pre>

<p>Use <a href="/tools/base64">our Base64 tool</a> with the Base64URL option to decode JWT payloads safely in your browser.</p>

<h3>Creating a Basic Auth Header</h3>

<pre><code># Encode credentials
echo -n "myusername:mysecretpassword" | base64
# Output: bXl1c2VybmFtZTpteXNlY3JldHBhc3N3b3Jk

# Use in HTTP header
Authorization: Basic bXl1c2VybmFtZTpteXNlY3JldHBhc3N3b3Jk</code></pre>

<h3>Embedding an Image as a Data URI</h3>

<pre><code>/* In CSS */
.icon {
  background-image: url("data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAUA...");
}

/* In HTML */
&lt;img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64,PHN2ZyB4bWxucz0iaHR0cDovL3d3dy53My5vcmcvMjAwMC9zdmciPjwvc3ZnPg=="&gt;</code></pre>

<h2>Security Considerations</h2>

<p>Base64 is an encoding scheme, not encryption. Anyone who intercepts a Base64-encoded string can instantly decode it. Do not confuse Base64 encoding with data security. Specifically:</p>

<ul>
  <li>HTTP Basic Auth credentials in Base64 are completely readable — always use HTTPS</li>
  <li>JWT payloads are readable to anyone who has the token — never put sensitive data you want to hide in a JWT payload</li>
  <li>Base64-encoded passwords in config files are not secure — use proper secret management</li>
</ul>

